data.enText: used when you want to emphasize how small, unimportant, etc. sb/sth is
It took her a mere 20 minutes to win.

data.chText: 他们的预算开支只有2%用于宣传。
data.enText: A mere 2% of their budget has been spent on publicity.

data.chText: 他看来那么年轻，只是个孩子。
data.enText: He seemed so young, a mere boy.

data.chText: 你已经得到了这份工作。面试不过是个形式。
data.enText: You've got the job. The interview will be a mere formality.
used when you are saying that the fact that a particular thing is present in a situation is enough to have an influence on that situation

data.chText: 他当时在场，这就足以让她害怕了。
data.enText: His mere presence (= just the fact that he was there) made her feel afraid.

data.chText: 他们愿意商谈，这就很不错了。
data.enText: The mere fact that they were prepared to talk was encouraging.

data.chText: 他一想到吃饭就觉得恶心。
data.enText: The mere thought of eating made him feel sick.

data.chText: 最细微的一丝烟就能使她感到不舒服。
data.enText: The merest (= the slightest) hint of smoke is enough to make her feel ill.

tr: a small pond of standing water

value.def: You use mere to emphasize how unimportant or inadequate something is, in comparison to the general situation you are describing.

example.ex: ...successful exhibitions which go beyond mere success...
example.tran: 不仅仅是成功而是大获成功的展览

example.ex: There is more to good health than the mere absence of disease...
example.tran: 身体健康不仅仅指不生病，还包括更多。

example.ex: In Poland, the faith has always meant more than mere religion...
example.tran: 在波兰，信仰的含义向来不仅仅指宗教。

example.ex: She'd never received the merest hint of any communication from him.
example.tran: 她从未得到他准备沟通的一丁点儿暗示。

value.def: You use mere to indicate that a quality or action that is usually unimportant has a very important or strong effect.

example.ex: The mere mention of food had triggered off hunger pangs...
example.tran: 单单提到食物就引起了阵阵饥饿感。

example.ex: Whenever there was a gap in the traffic the merest pressure on the accelerator was enough to close it...
example.tran: 每当车流里出现了一点儿空距，只要稍稍一踩油门，空距就没有了。

example.ex: The team manager has been quick to clamp down on the merest hint of complacency.
example.tran: 球队主教练很快就消除了自满的小苗头。

value.tran: 极小的，微不足道的，单单(表示虽小却有重要影响)

value.def: You use mere to emphasize how small a particular amount or number is.

example.ex: Sixty per cent of teachers are women, but a mere 5 percent of women are heads and deputies...
example.tran: 有60%的教师是女性，但是担任校长和副校长的女性仅占5%。

example.ex: Tickets are a mere £7.50 at the door...
For the past two decades, North Carolina taxed cigarettes at a mere 2 cents a packet.
example.tran: 过去20年里，北卡罗来纳州的香烟税仅为每包2美分。

value.tran: 只不过，仅仅(用于强调数量之小)

usage_note.note: Mere does not have a comparative form. The superlative form merest is used to emphasize how small something is, rather than in comparisons.
usage_note.translation: mere 没有比较级，最高级 merest 并无比较之义，而是用来强调极其微小。
